{
  "style": "APA",
  "texts": [
    "The term \"advanced saliency maps\" is used here to refer to saliency maps designed for a specific application, while still showing only one map per image.",
    "These specialisations were developed for particular tasks such as object detection (Zhao & Chan, 2023), for particular image types such as faces (John et al., 2021) or for particular image distortions such as privacy blurring (Zhang et al., 2022).",
    "Moreover, saliency maps were adapted to contain information about the uncertainty of feature relevance (Slack et al., 2021).",
    "All these advanced methods yielded superior performance compared to standard saliency maps.",
    "Several studies compared standard saliency maps to extensions and combinations with other types of XAI."
  ],
  "correct_citations": [
    "These specialisations were developed for particular tasks such as object detection (Zhao & Chan, 2023), for particular image types such as faces (John et al., 2021) or for particular image distortions such as privacy blurring (Zhang et al., 2022).",
